  "notes": "This is essentially Euclid’s classic proof by contradiction. Assuming finitely many primes \$p_1,\\dots,p_n\$ and forming \$N=\\prod_{i=1}^n p_i+1\$, one concludes that \$N\$ is either prime (giving a new prime) or composite with a prime divisor not among \$p_1,\\dots,p_n\$, contradicting finiteness.",
  "suggestions": "Make the key divisibility step explicit: for each \$i\$, \$p_i\\mid \\prod_{j=1}^n p_j\$ implies \$p_i\\nmid N\$ since \$N\\equiv 1\\pmod{p_i}\$. Hence no listed prime divides \$N\$, so any prime factor of \$N\$ is new."
}

